fr.sii.ogham.core.builder

Class LookupMappingResourceResolverBuilder

  • java.lang.Object
    • fr.sii.ogham.core.builder.LookupMappingResourceResolverBuilder
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Builder<LookupMappingResolver>

    public class LookupMappingResourceResolverBuilder
extends Object
implements Builder<LookupMappingResolver>

    Builder used to help construct the resource resolution. Resource resolution is based on a lookup prefix. The lookup prefix is case sensitive and must end with a ':'. It must not contain another ':' character.

    For example, a resource path could be "classpath:/email/hello.html". The lookup prefix is "classpath:".

    The lookup can also be empty in order to define a kind of default resolver if no lookup is provided. The resource path could then be "/email/hello.html". The resolver associated to empty string lookup will be used in this case.

    By default, the builder will use the following template resolvers:
    • Resolver that is able to handle classpath resolution ( ClassPathResolver)
    • Resolver that is able to handle file resolution (FileResolver)

      • useDefaults

        public LookupMappingResourceResolverBuilder useDefaults()
        Tells the builder to use the default template resolvers:
        • Resolver that is able to handle classpath resolution ( ClassPathResolver). The lookup prefix is "classpath:"
        • Resolver that is able to handle file resolution ( FileResolver). The lookup is "file:"
        • Resolver that is able to handle string directly ( StringResourceResolver). The lookup is "string:"
        • Default resolver if no lookup is used ( ClassPathResolver)
        Returns:
        this builder instance for fluent use

      • withLookupResolver

        public LookupMappingResourceResolverBuilder withLookupResolver(String lookup,
                                                               ResourceResolver resolver)
        Register a lookup resolver. The lookup is like JNDI lookup. It indicates using a simple string how to handle the provided path or URL. For example:
        • "classpath:/foo" indicates that the provided path represents a classpath entry.
        • "file:/tmp" indicates that the provided path represents a file located on the system.
        Parameters:
        lookup - the lookup name (without the : character)
        resolver - the resolver implementation
        Returns:
        The current builder for fluent use

      • withPrefix

        public LookupMappingResourceResolverBuilder withPrefix(String prefix)
        Set the prefix for template lookup. This prefix is used for all lookup methods. The aim is to define only the name of the template (or a subset) and the system will find it for you. It avoids to explicitly write the whole path and let you change the lookup method easily. For example:
        • You have one template located into /foo/template/createAccount.html
        • You have one template located into /foo/template/resetPassword.html
        So you can set the prefix to /foo/template/ and then reference the templates using the file name:
        • createAccount.html
        • resetPassword.html
        Parameters:
        prefix - the prefix for template resolution
        Returns:
        The current builder for fluent use

      • withSuffix

        public LookupMappingResourceResolverBuilder withSuffix(String suffix)
        Set the suffix for resolution lookup. This suffix is used for all lookup methods. The aim is to define only the name of the resource (or a subset) and the system will find it for you. It avoids to explicitly write the whole path and let you change the lookup method easily. For example:
        • You have one resource located into /foo/resource/createAccount.html
        • You have one resource located into /foo/resource/resetPassword.html
        So you can set the prefix to /foo/resource/, the suffix to .html and then reference the resources using the file name:
        • createAccount
        • resetPassword
        Parameters:
        suffix - the suffix for resource resolution
        Returns:
        The current builder for fluent use
